    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "272c64f2_5d020fe3",
        "filename": "src/core/SkCanvas.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 5
      },
      "lineNbr": 2461,
      "author": {
        "id": 8341
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-12-07T19:10:41Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "So it\u0027s a little trickier than that, but I\u0027m thinking we can have an init/canonize_paint function that covers our use cases and is easy enough to read. The challenge is some places force fill, or force stroke, and others want no path effect, and others want no mask filter (and no path effect). Some also have null paint inputs that need to be converted to the default paint.\n\n   enum PaintRules {\n      kForceFillStyle \u003d 0x1,\n      kForceStrokeStyle \u003d 0x2,\n      kNoPathEffect \u003d 0x4,\n      kNoMaskFilter \u003d 0x8\n   };\n\n   SkTCopyOnWrite\u003cSkPaint\u003e init_paint(const SkPaint* origPaint, PaintRules bitmask) {\n       SkTCopyOnWrite\u003cSkPaint\u003e paint(origPaint);\n       paint.initIfNeeded(); // new function, initializes the fLazy if no obj set\n       if (bitmask\u0026 kForceFillStyle \u0026\u0026 paint-\u003egetStyle() !\u003d kFill) {\n           paint.writable()-\u003esetStyle(kFill);\n       }\n       // etc. for the flags\n       return paint;\n    }\n\n    The init_image_paint() would have force-fill, no-path-effect. drawVertices, drawPaint would be force-fill, no-path-effect, no-mask-filter. drawPoints would be force-stroke.\n\nYou can see a version of this using copy-on-write for just the drawImage family here: https://skia-review.googlesource.com/c/skia/+/341056 What do you think?",
      "parentUuid": "e605601c_524bf1b0",
      "revId": "70b0c520af88e5b162a5f23d73f19e7b4db8f513",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02"
    },
